NORMALISED EXTRACT
for statement
- Syntax: for (initialization; condition; afterthought) statement
- Execution order: initialization -> evaluate condition -> execute statement -> afterthought -> repeat.
- Initialization commonly declares loop counters (let i = 0); condition must eventually evaluate to false to avoid infinite loops.

while and do...while
- while(condition) statement: test condition before executing statement; may execute zero times if condition false initially.
- do statement while(condition): execute statement once, then evaluate condition to decide continuation; guarantees at least one execution.

for...in vs for...of
- for...in iterates enumerable property names of an object (property keys). Not recommended for arrays because it enumerates user-defined properties in addition to numeric indexes.
- for...of iterates over iterable values (Array, Map, Set, arguments, strings). Use for...of for array element iteration.

break and continue semantics
- break; terminates the innermost enclosing loop or switch immediately.
- continue; terminates the current iteration and continues with the next iteration (for loops jump to increment expression, while loops re-evaluate condition).
- Both support optional labels: break label; continue label; to target an outer labeled statement.

Labeled statements and control flow
- Format: label: statement
- Use labels to break or continue outer loops from inner loops (e.g., break outerLoopLabel;).
- Excessive use of labels reduces readability; prefer structured control where possible.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Avoid infinite loops by ensuring loop variables are updated to make condition false at some point.
- Use block statements { } to execute multiple statements inside loop bodies.
- Prefer for loops or for...of for predictable iteration and performance; for...in is useful for object property enumeration only.

REFERENCE DETAILS
- No runtime API required beyond language constructs. Use loop control statements as specified in ECMAScript standard: for, while, do...while, for...in, for...of, break, continue, labels.
- Implementation patterns: use for (let i = 0; i < len; i++) for indexed arrays; use for (const v of iterable) for value iteration; use labeled break to escape nested loops sparingly.

